REST (Representational State Transfer) and gRPC are two dominant API styles for microservices, each with distinct trade-offs.

REST over HTTP/1.1 or HTTP/2:
- Text-based (JSON/XML): human-readable, easy to inspect with curl/Postman
- Stateless, resource-oriented design (nouns as URLs, HTTP verbs for actions)
- Universal: browsers, mobile clients, third parties all speak REST natively
- Loose coupling: no shared schema required (though OpenAPI helps)
- Slower: JSON serialization/deserialization is CPU-intensive; text is larger than binary
- No built-in streaming or bidirectional communication (workarounds: SSE, WebSocket)

gRPC (Google Remote Procedure Call):
- Binary protocol using Protocol Buffers (protobuf) — 3-10x smaller payload, much faster serialization
- Strongly typed: `.proto` schema shared between client and server, code generated automatically
- HTTP/2 native: multiplexing, header compression, full-duplex streaming
- Four communication modes: unary, server streaming, client streaming, bidirectional streaming
- Harder to debug (binary wire format), limited browser support (needs grpc-web proxy)

Performance comparison:
```
REST JSON:  ~500 bytes per typical response, ~200μs serialization
gRPC proto: ~50 bytes same data,            ~20μs serialization
Throughput advantage: gRPC 5-10x higher RPS under same hardware
```

Java REST example (Spring Boot):
```java
@RestController
public class OrderController {
    @GetMapping("/orders/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<OrderDto> getOrder(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(orderService.findById(id));
    }
}
```

Java gRPC example (generated stub usage):
```java
// Proto-generated stub — strongly typed, no manual serialization
OrderServiceGrpc.OrderServiceBlockingStub stub =
    OrderServiceGrpc.newBlockingStub(channel);
GetOrderResponse response = stub.getOrder(
    GetOrderRequest.newBuilder().setOrderId(42).build()
);
```

gRPC streaming (bidirectional — e.g., live order tracking):
```java
StreamObserver<OrderUpdate> requestObserver = stub.trackOrder(
    new StreamObserver<TrackingEvent>() {
        public void onNext(TrackingEvent event) { updateUI(event); }
        public void onError(Throwable t) { handleError(t); }
        public void onCompleted() { closeConnection(); }
    }
);
```

Decision guide:
| Criterion              | REST             | gRPC                    |
|------------------------|------------------|-------------------------|
| Public/external API    | Yes              | No (limited browser)    |
| Internal microservices | OK               | Preferred               |
| Streaming data         | Limited (SSE)    | First-class support     |
| Mobile clients         | Yes              | Yes (with proto libs)   |
| Debugging ease         | High             | Lower (need tools)      |
| Performance priority   | Medium           | High                    |

Production best practice: expose REST externally for broad client compatibility; use gRPC internally for service-to-service calls where latency and throughput matter. Use an API gateway to translate between the two.

