HikariCP is the fastest Java connection pool and the default in Spring Boot. Understanding its internals helps you tune it correctly and diagnose production issues.

Core data structure — ConcurrentBag:
HikariCP does NOT use a simple blocking queue. It uses a custom lock-free structure called ConcurrentBag:
```
ConcurrentBag internals:
  threadLocalList  -> thread-local cache of recently used connections
  sharedList       -> lock-free list of all pool entries (CopyOnWriteArrayList)
  waiters          -> count of threads waiting (AtomicInteger)
  handoffQueue     -> SynchronousQueue for direct handoff to waiting threads
```

Connection acquisition algorithm (ultra-fast path):
```java
// Simplified HikariCP acquisition logic:
// 1. Check thread-local cache first (zero contention)
List<PoolEntry> localList = threadLocalList.get();
for (PoolEntry entry : localList) {
    if (entry.compareAndSet(STATE_NOT_IN_USE, STATE_IN_USE)) {
        return entry; // fastest path: O(1), no lock, no queue
    }
}
// 2. Scan shared list (lock-free CAS)
for (PoolEntry entry : sharedList) {
    if (entry.compareAndSet(STATE_NOT_IN_USE, STATE_IN_USE)) {
        localList.add(entry); // add to thread-local for next time
        return entry;
    }
}
// 3. Wait on handoff queue (blocking, with timeout)
return handoffQueue.poll(connectionTimeout, MILLISECONDS);
```

Why HikariCP is faster than c3p0/DBCP2:
- Thread-local caching: same thread reuses same connection with zero CAS contention
- Lock-free path: uses AtomicInteger state (NOT_IN_USE=0, IN_USE=1, REMOVED=-1) with CAS
- Minimal object creation: reuses PoolEntry wrappers, no new objects per acquisition
- Direct handoff: when a connection is returned while a thread is waiting, it's handed directly (bypasses queue)

Connection lifecycle management:
```
[INIT] -> minimumIdle connections created at startup
[IDLE] -> sitting in pool, keepalive ping sent every keepaliveTime
[IN_USE] -> borrowed by a thread
[RETURNED] -> thread closes connection -> returned to pool (or handed to waiter)
[EVICTED] -> exceeded maxLifetime or failed validation -> removed, new one created
```

Keepalive and validation:
```java
// HikariCP sends a lightweight keepalive query to prevent firewall timeouts:
config.setKeepaliveTime(30_000);    // ping idle connections every 30s
config.setConnectionTestQuery("SELECT 1"); // or use isValid() which is faster
config.setMaxLifetime(1_800_000);   // recycle connections every 30min (before DB timeout)
```

Key configuration properties explained:
```java
HikariConfig config = new HikariConfig();
// Maximum connections in pool — do not set this too high!
config.setMaximumPoolSize(20);
// Minimum idle connections maintained
config.setMinimumIdle(5);
// Time to wait for a connection before throwing SQLException
config.setConnectionTimeout(30_000);  // 30 seconds
// How long a connection can sit idle before being removed
config.setIdleTimeout(600_000);       // 10 minutes
// Maximum age of any connection (recycle before DB kills it)
config.setMaxLifetime(1_800_000);     // 30 minutes
// Leak detection: log stack trace if connection held > N ms
config.setLeakDetectionThreshold(5_000); // 5 seconds — invaluable in production
```

Connection leak detection (production essential):
LeakDetectionThreshold logs the stack trace of the code that borrowed a connection but never returned it:
```
WARN  HikariPool - Connection leak detection triggered for connection
  com.zaxxer.hikari.pool.ProxyLeakedConnection@...
  Stack trace at acquisition:
    at com.example.OrderRepository.findAll(OrderRepository.java:42)
    at com.example.OrderService.processAll(OrderService.java:88)
```

Monitoring HikariCP metrics (Micrometer integration):
```java
config.setMetricRegistry(meterRegistry); // Prometheus/Grafana
// Exposes: hikaricp.connections.active, .idle, .pending, .timeout
```

Production tuning checklist:
- Set leakDetectionThreshold (5000ms) to catch unreturned connections
- Set maxLifetime less than your database's wait_timeout (MySQL) or idle session timeout
- Monitor hikaricp.connections.pending — if consistently > 0, pool is undersized
- Never set maximumPoolSize > database's max_connections / number_of_app_instances

