A thread pool is a managed collection of pre-created worker threads that execute submitted tasks, avoiding the overhead of creating and destroying a thread for each task. Java's ThreadPoolExecutor is the core implementation behind all executor services.

ThreadPoolExecutor parameters:
```java
new ThreadPoolExecutor(
    int corePoolSize,       // always-alive threads
    int maximumPoolSize,    // max threads under load
    long keepAliveTime,     // how long extra threads live when idle
    TimeUnit unit,
    BlockingQueue<Runnable> workQueue,  // holds waiting tasks
    RejectedExecutionHandler handler    // what to do when queue full + max threads reached
);
```

How task submission works (the algorithm):
```
1. If active threads < corePoolSize -> create new thread (even if idle threads exist)
2. If active threads >= corePoolSize -> add task to queue
3. If queue is full AND active threads < maximumPoolSize -> create new thread
4. If queue is full AND active threads == maximumPoolSize -> RejectedExecutionHandler fires
```

Diagram:
```
Submit task
    |
    v
[core threads full?] --No--> Create core thread
    |
   Yes
    v
[queue full?] --No--> Add to queue (wait)
    |
   Yes
    v
[max threads full?] --No--> Create extra thread
    |
   Yes
    v
 RejectedExecutionHandler (CallerRunsPolicy / AbortPolicy / etc.)
```

CPU-bound task tuning:
```java
// CPU-bound: threads = N_cores + 1
// The +1 compensates for occasional page faults / OS interrupts
int cpuCores = Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors();
ExecutorService cpuPool = new ThreadPoolExecutor(
    cpuCores + 1,                    // core
    cpuCores + 1,                    // max (fixed size — no benefit from more)
    0L, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS,
    new LinkedBlockingQueue<>(1000), // bounded queue
    new ThreadPoolExecutor.CallerRunsPolicy() // backpressure: caller thread executes
);
```

I/O-bound task tuning:
```java
// I/O-bound: threads = cores * (1 + wait_time / compute_time)
// Example: DB call takes 50ms, processing takes 5ms
// wait_ratio = 50/5 = 10, so threads = 4 * (1 + 10) = 44
int ioThreads = cpuCores * (1 + avgWaitMs / avgComputeMs);

// Or use a cached thread pool for bursty I/O (auto-scales, but unbounded!)
ExecutorService ioPool = Executors.newCachedThreadPool(); // dangerous without bounds

// Better: bounded cached pool
ExecutorService safIoPool = new ThreadPoolExecutor(
    10,                              // always keep 10 alive
    200,                             // max under spike
    60L, TimeUnit.SECONDS,           // shrink after 60s idle
    new SynchronousQueue<>()         // no queue: direct handoff forces new thread creation
);
```

Rejection policies:
```java
// AbortPolicy (default): throws RejectedExecutionException
// CallerRunsPolicy: calling thread executes the task (backpressure)
// DiscardPolicy: silently drops the task (data loss!)
// DiscardOldestPolicy: drops oldest queued task, then retries

// Custom policy for metrics:
handler = (task, executor) -> {
    rejectionCounter.increment(); // record metric
    log.warn("Task rejected: pool={}, queue={}",
        executor.getActiveCount(), executor.getQueue().size());
    throw new RejectedExecutionException("System overloaded");
};
```

Monitoring (critical in production):
```java
ThreadPoolExecutor pool = (ThreadPoolExecutor) executor;
// Sample these metrics every 10 seconds:
log.info("Pool stats: active={}, queued={}, completed={}, poolSize={}",
    pool.getActiveCount(),        // running right now
    pool.getQueue().size(),       // waiting in queue
    pool.getCompletedTaskCount(), // total finished
    pool.getPoolSize());          // current thread count

// Warning signs:
// queue.size() > 0 consistently  -> pool undersized or tasks too slow
// rejection rate > 0             -> system overloaded, scale up
// activeCount == maximumPoolSize -> at capacity
```

Common mistake: using Executors.newFixedThreadPool() with an unbounded LinkedBlockingQueue. Under sustained overload, the queue grows without bound, consuming heap memory until OOM, while the system appears to be working (tasks just queue up silently).

Production best practice: always use bounded queues, always set a rejection handler, always expose pool metrics to your monitoring system.

