ForkJoinPool is a specialized thread pool designed for divide-and-conquer recursive parallelism. It is the engine behind Java parallel streams and CompletableFuture. Understanding it is essential for both using it correctly and avoiding its pitfalls.

The core idea — Fork and Join:
```
fork() -> submit a subtask to the pool (asynchronous)
join() -> wait for a subtask to complete

Big problem
    fork -> Left half       fork -> Right half
              |                       |
           fork -> LL   fork -> LR  fork -> RL  fork -> RR
              |           |           |           |
           solve()      solve()    solve()     solve()
              |           |           |           |
           join()       join()     join()      join()
              \           /           \           /
               result_L               result_R
                        \             /
                         final_result
```

Work-stealing algorithm:
Each worker thread has its own double-ended deque (deque). When a thread is idle, it STEALS tasks from the TAIL of another thread's deque (while the owner works from the HEAD). This minimizes contention on the shared structure.

```
Thread 1 deque: [T1, T2, T3, T4] <- T1 executed by Thread 1
Thread 2 deque: [     empty     ] <- Thread 2 steals T4 from Thread 1's tail

Result: both threads work in parallel with minimal coordination
```

ForkJoinTask implementations:
```java
// RecursiveTask<V>: returns a value
class MergeSortTask extends RecursiveTask<int[]> {
    private final int[] array;
    private final int lo, hi;
    private static final int THRESHOLD = 1000; // tune this!

    MergeSortTask(int[] array, int lo, int hi) {
        this.array = array; this.lo = lo; this.hi = hi;
    }

    @Override
    protected int[] compute() {
        if (hi - lo <= THRESHOLD) {
            return sortSequentially(array, lo, hi); // base case
        }
        int mid = (lo + hi) / 2;
        MergeSortTask left  = new MergeSortTask(array, lo, mid);
        MergeSortTask right = new MergeSortTask(array, mid, hi);

        left.fork();              // submit left to pool asynchronously
        int[] rightResult = right.compute(); // compute right in THIS thread
        int[] leftResult  = left.join();     // wait for left

        return merge(leftResult, rightResult);
    }
}

ForkJoinPool pool = new ForkJoinPool();
int[] sorted = pool.invoke(new MergeSortTask(array, 0, array.length));
```

Parallel streams use the common ForkJoinPool:
```java
// This runs in ForkJoinPool.commonPool() — shared across the JVM!
List<Integer> result = list.parallelStream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
    .map(n -> n * n)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

// WARNING: blocking operations in parallel streams starve the common pool
// BAD: this blocks common pool threads, hurting all parallel operations JVM-wide
list.parallelStream().forEach(item -> {
    Thread.sleep(100); // NEVER block in parallel stream!
    dbRepository.save(item);
});

// GOOD: use a custom pool for blocking work
ForkJoinPool customPool = new ForkJoinPool(20); // more threads for I/O
customPool.submit(() ->
    list.parallelStream().forEach(item -> dbRepository.save(item))
).get();
```

Pool sizing:
```java
// Default: ForkJoinPool.commonPool() uses (N_cores - 1) threads
// Tune via JVM flag:
// -Djava.util.concurrent.ForkJoinPool.common.parallelism=8

// Custom pool:
ForkJoinPool customPool = new ForkJoinPool(
    Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors(), // parallelism
    ForkJoinPool.defaultForkJoinWorkerThreadFactory,
    null,  // uncaught exception handler
    false  // asyncMode: false = LIFO (better for recursive), true = FIFO
);
```

When to use ForkJoinPool vs ThreadPoolExecutor:
- ForkJoinPool: recursive decomposition, parallel streams, CPU-bound divide-and-conquer, work is roughly uniform size
- ThreadPoolExecutor: independent tasks, I/O-bound work, tasks of varying size, need fine-grained rejection/queue control

Key pitfall: never perform blocking I/O inside ForkJoinPool tasks. Pool threads are CPU-bound workers; blocking them starves other tasks and defeats the purpose. Use managedBlock() if blocking is unavoidable:
```java
ForkJoinPool.managedBlock(new ForkJoinPool.ManagedBlocker() {
    public boolean block() throws InterruptedException {
        result = blockingCall(); // pool knows this thread is blocked, adds a spare
        return true;
    }
    public boolean isReleasable() { return result != null; }
});
```

