A memory leak in Java occurs when objects that are no longer logically needed remain strongly reachable — held by a reference the GC cannot break — preventing their collection. Unlike C/C++, Java cannot leak memory by forgetting to free it, but it absolutely can leak by keeping unneeded references alive.

Why the GC cannot help:
The GC only frees objects with no reachable references. If your code maintains a reference (even accidentally), the object is live as far as GC is concerned.

```
LEAK:  GC Root -> LeakyCache (static) -> [Order1, Order2, ..., Order1_000_000]
       GC cannot collect any Order because LeakyCache holds them all!

NO LEAK: After cache.remove(order), no path from GC root -> Order -> collected
```

Common memory leak patterns in Java:

1. Static collection never cleared:
```java
// LEAK: static map grows forever, never cleared
public class SessionManager {
    private static final Map<String, Session> sessions = new HashMap<>();

    public static void addSession(String id, Session s) {
        sessions.put(id, s); // added but never removed on logout/expiry
    }
    // Sessions pile up even after users log out
}

// FIX: Use evicting cache
private static final Map<String, Session> sessions =
    Collections.synchronizedMap(
        new LinkedHashMap<>() {
            protected boolean removeEldestEntry(Map.Entry e) {
                return size() > 10_000; // evict when too large
            }
        }
    );
// Or better: Caffeine/Guava cache with TTL
Cache<String, Session> sessions = Caffeine.newBuilder()
    .maximumSize(10_000)
    .expireAfterAccess(30, TimeUnit.MINUTES)
    .build();
```

2. Event listeners / callbacks never unregistered:
```java
// LEAK: every call to addListener keeps listener alive
class EventBus {
    private final List<EventListener> listeners = new ArrayList<>();
    public void addListener(EventListener l) { listeners.add(l); }
    // removeListener() exists but callers forget to call it
}

// FIX: Use WeakReference so listeners can be GC'd if caller drops them
private final List<WeakReference<EventListener>> listeners = new CopyOnWriteArrayList<>();
public void addListener(EventListener l) {
    listeners.add(new WeakReference<>(l));
}
// Clean up dead refs during dispatch
listeners.removeIf(ref -> ref.get() == null);
```

3. ThreadLocal not removed in thread pool (servlet containers):
```java
// LEAK: thread pool threads are reused; ThreadLocal values persist across requests
private static final ThreadLocal<UserContext> userContext = new ThreadLocal<>();

// In a servlet or filter:
public void doFilter(Request req, Response resp, FilterChain chain) {
    userContext.set(new UserContext(req.getUser()));
    try {
        chain.doFilter(req, resp);
    } finally {
        userContext.remove(); // CRITICAL: always remove in finally block
    }
}
```

4. Inner class holding reference to outer class:
```java
// LEAK: anonymous Runnable keeps reference to enclosing Activity/Controller
executor.submit(new Runnable() {
    public void run() {
        // implicitly holds reference to outer class instance!
        updateUI(outerField);
    }
});

// FIX: use static nested class or lambda capturing only necessary data
String data = this.data; // copy only what's needed
executor.submit(() -> process(data)); // lambda, but still captures 'data'
```

5. ClassLoader leak (common in application servers):
```java
// LEAK: if application ClassLoader is not GC'd, all its classes stay in Metaspace
// Cause: static reference to a class from the app ClassLoader held by container
// Example: JDBC driver registered in DriverManager by app ClassLoader
// Fix: deregister on undeploy
DriverManager.deregisterDriver(driver); // call in ServletContextListener.contextDestroyed()
```

Detection workflow:
```bash
# Step 1: Monitor heap trend (linear growth = leak)
jstat -gcutil <pid> 5000  # sample every 5 seconds
# If Old Gen % keeps rising without Full GC clearing it -> leak

# Step 2: Capture heap dump
jmap -dump:live,format=b,file=heap.bin <pid>
# Or configure automatic dump on OOM:
# -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError -XX:HeapDumpPath=/tmp/

# Step 3: Analyze in Eclipse MAT or VisualVM
# Look for: Leak Suspects report, Dominator Tree (what object holds most memory)
# Search for unexpected object counts (1M Order objects when you expect 1000)
```

Production monitoring checklist:
- Alert on Old Gen heap growth rate > X MB/hour over a sustained window
- Compare heap before/after major GC cycles — should return to baseline
- Track object count by class with JMX or async-profiler
- Use `jcmd <pid> GC.heap_info` for quick health check without full heap dump

