OutOfMemoryError (OOM) and StackOverflowError are both fatal JVM errors (subclasses of Error, not Exception), but they affect completely different memory regions and have different root causes, diagnostics, and fixes.

Memory architecture context:
```
JVM Memory:
+----------------------------------+  <- Heap: objects live here (GC managed)
|  Young Gen  |    Old Gen         |     controlled by -Xmx
+----------------------------------+
|         Metaspace                |     native memory, controlled by -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize
+----------------------------------+
|  Thread 1 Stack                  |  <- Stack: method frames live here (per-thread)
|  Thread 2 Stack                  |     controlled by -Xss per thread
|  Thread N Stack                  |
+----------------------------------+
|  Direct / Off-heap Memory        |     NIO ByteBuffers, native libs
+----------------------------------+
```

OutOfMemoryError — heap or other memory exhausted:

OOM has multiple distinct sub-messages, each pointing to a different cause:

```java
// 1. Java heap space — most common
// Heap is full: GC cannot reclaim enough memory
// Causes: memory leak, heap too small, allocating massive data structures
java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space
// Fix: -Xmx4g, fix memory leak, reduce allocation

// 2. GC overhead limit exceeded
// JVM spending >98% time in GC, freeing <2% heap per cycle
// Indicator of near-total heap exhaustion or severe leak
java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: GC overhead limit exceeded
// Fix: fix leak, increase heap

// 3. Metaspace — class metadata area full
// Too many classes loaded (dynamic proxies, code generation, plugin systems)
java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: Metaspace
// Fix: -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=512m, fix classloader leaks, reduce generated classes

// 4. Direct buffer memory — off-heap NIO buffers
// Common with Netty, direct ByteBuffer allocation without cleanup
java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: Direct buffer memory
// Fix: -XX:MaxDirectMemorySize=1g, ensure ByteBuffer cleanup, tune Netty pool

// 5. Unable to create new native thread
// OS-level thread limit reached (ulimit, process limit)
java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: unable to create new native thread
// Fix: reduce thread count, use virtual threads (Java 21), increase OS limits

// 6. request size bytes for reason — heap fragmentation
java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space (request 1073741824 bytes)
// Large array allocation fails despite technically enough total heap (fragmented)
```

Code that triggers OOM:
```java
// Memory leak -> OOM
Map<String, byte[]> leak = new HashMap<>();
for (int i = 0; ; i++) {
    leak.put("key" + i, new byte[1024 * 1024]); // 1MB per entry, never freed
} // -> OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space

// Massive allocation
byte[] huge = new byte[Integer.MAX_VALUE]; // 2GB -> likely OOM

// Too many threads
for (int i = 0; i < 100_000; i++) {
    new Thread(() -> { while(true) {} }).start(); // -> unable to create native thread
}
```

StackOverflowError — thread stack exhausted:

Each method call adds a frame to the thread's stack (local variables, parameters, return address). Default stack size is 256KB-1MB. Deep recursion adds frames until the stack is full.

```java
// Classic: unbounded recursion
public int factorial(int n) {
    return n * factorial(n - 1); // missing base case!
    // Each call adds a frame: ~50 bytes
    // 512KB stack / 50 bytes = ~10,000 frames before StackOverflow
}
// -> java.lang.StackOverflowError

// Subtle: mutual recursion
public boolean isEven(int n) { return n == 0 || isOdd(n - 1); }
public boolean isOdd(int n)  { return n != 0 && isEven(n - 1); }
// isEven(1_000_000) -> StackOverflowError

// Fix 1: Add base case
public int factorial(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return 1;          // base case
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
}

// Fix 2: Convert to iterative (always safe)
public int factorial(int n) {
    int result = 1;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) result *= i;
    return result;
}

// Fix 3: Increase stack size for legitimate deep recursion
// -Xss4m  increases each thread's stack to 4MB
// Or create thread with custom stack:
new Thread(null, () -> deepRecursiveWork(), "deep-worker", 8 * 1024 * 1024).start();
```

Key differences at a glance:
```
| Property        | OutOfMemoryError           | StackOverflowError        |
|-----------------|----------------------------|---------------------------|
| Memory region   | Heap / Metaspace / Native  | Thread stack              |
| Root cause      | Too many live objects      | Too many nested calls     |
| Recoverable?    | Sometimes (try/catch Error)| Sometimes                 |
| Trigger         | GC cannot free enough      | Stack frame limit hit     |
| Fix direction   | Tune heap, fix leak        | Fix recursion, tune -Xss  |
| GC involved?    | Yes (GC runs first)        | No (GC not involved)      |
| Thread-specific?| Affects whole JVM          | Affects only that thread  |
```

Diagnostic commands:
```bash
# For OOM: get heap dump
jmap -dump:live,format=b,file=heap.bin <pid>
jcmd <pid> GC.heap_info

# For StackOverflow: get thread dump
jstack <pid> | grep -A 20 "StackOverflow"
jcmd <pid> Thread.print
# Look for the deepest recursive call in the stack trace
```

