The ClassLoader hierarchy is the mechanism by which the JVM finds and loads .class bytecode files. Understanding it is critical for diagnosing ClassCastException from loader mismatches, building plugin systems, and avoiding Metaspace leaks from ClassLoader accumulation.

The three built-in ClassLoaders (Java 8 and earlier):
```
Bootstrap ClassLoader
  |  Loads: JDK core classes (java.lang.*, java.util.*, etc.)
  |  Source: rt.jar / jre/lib/*.jar (or JDK modules in Java 9+)
  |  Implemented in: Native C code (not a Java object)
  |
Extension ClassLoader
  |  Loads: Standard extensions from jre/lib/ext/*.jar
  |  Implemented in: sun.misc.Launcher$ExtClassLoader
  |
Application (System) ClassLoader
     Loads: Your application classpath (-cp, CLASSPATH env var)
     Implemented in: sun.misc.Launcher$AppClassLoader
```

Java 9+ module system changes:
```
Bootstrap ClassLoader  <- java.base module
Platform ClassLoader   <- replaces Extension ClassLoader
Application ClassLoader <- your code
```

The Delegation (Parent-First) Model:
Before attempting to load a class itself, a ClassLoader ALWAYS asks its parent first. Only if the parent cannot find it does the child attempt to load it.

```java
// Simplified ClassLoader.loadClass() logic:
protected Class<?> loadClass(String name, boolean resolve) throws ClassNotFoundException {
    // 1. Check if already loaded (cache)
    Class<?> c = findLoadedClass(name);
    if (c == null) {
        // 2. Delegate to parent first
        try {
            c = parent.loadClass(name, false); // parent-first!
        } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
            // 3. Parent couldn't find it — try ourselves
            c = findClass(name); // looks in our own classpath
        }
    }
    if (resolve) resolveClass(c);
    return c;
}
```

Why parent-first? Security and consistency:
- Prevents malicious code from replacing java.lang.String with a custom version
- Ensures all code shares the same java.lang.Object (they'd be incompatible types if loaded twice)
- Prevents version conflicts: JDK classes always loaded by Bootstrap, never overridden

ASCII delegation diagram:
```
Request: load "com.example.OrderService"

AppClassLoader
  -> "Bootstrap, do you have it?"  Bootstrap: "No"
  -> "Platform, do you have it?"   Platform:  "No"
  -> "I'll find it myself"         AppClassLoader: finds it in /app/classes -> LOADED

Request: load "java.lang.String"
  -> "Bootstrap, do you have it?"  Bootstrap: "Yes!" -> returns Bootstrap's String
  AppClassLoader never touches java.lang.String
```

Custom ClassLoaders — when and why:
```java
// Plugin system: each plugin gets its own ClassLoader
// Allows multiple versions of the same library to coexist
public class PluginClassLoader extends URLClassLoader {
    public PluginClassLoader(URL[] pluginJars, ClassLoader parent) {
        super(pluginJars, parent);
    }

    // Child-first (parent-last) override for plugin isolation:
    @Override
    protected Class<?> loadClass(String name, boolean resolve)
            throws ClassNotFoundException {
        // Load plugin classes ourselves first (before delegating to parent)
        // But always delegate system/API classes to parent for compatibility
        if (name.startsWith("com.example.pluginapi.")) {
            return super.loadClass(name, resolve); // use parent for shared API
        }
        synchronized (getClassLoadingLock(name)) {
            Class<?> c = findLoadedClass(name);
            if (c == null) {
                try {
                    c = findClass(name); // try plugin jar first
                } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
                    c = super.loadClass(name, resolve); // fall back to parent
                }
            }
            if (resolve) resolveClass(c);
            return c;
        }
    }
}

// Loading a plugin:
URL[] pluginJars = { new File("/plugins/analytics-1.0.jar").toURI().toURL() };
try (PluginClassLoader loader = new PluginClassLoader(pluginJars, getClass().getClassLoader())) {
    Class<?> pluginClass = loader.loadClass("com.analytics.AnalyticsPlugin");
    Plugin plugin = (Plugin) pluginClass.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();
    plugin.initialize();
} // URLClassLoader.close() prevents ClassLoader leak
```

ClassLoader identity rule — the same class loaded by different loaders are DIFFERENT types:
```java
// This will throw ClassCastException!
ClassLoader loaderA = new URLClassLoader(new URL[]{jarUrl});
ClassLoader loaderB = new URLClassLoader(new URL[]{jarUrl});
Class<?> classFromA = loaderA.loadClass("com.example.Widget");
Class<?> classFromB = loaderB.loadClass("com.example.Widget");
Object widgetFromA = classFromA.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();
// ClassCastException: classFromB cannot cast classFromA instance
Object wrong = classFromB.cast(widgetFromA);

// Debug: print classloader
System.out.println(widgetFromA.getClass().getClassLoader()); // shows which loader
```

ClassLoader leak (critical Metaspace issue):
```java
// LEAK: ClassLoader not closed -> all its classes stay in Metaspace forever
// Common in application servers on hot redeploy (classes accumulate)
URLClassLoader leakyLoader = new URLClassLoader(urls);
// ... load classes ...
// forgot: leakyLoader.close() and nulling all references

// FIX: use try-with-resources or explicit close
try (URLClassLoader loader = new URLClassLoader(urls, parent)) {
    // use loader
} // auto-closed, classes eligible for GC when no more references

// Monitor Metaspace for leak:
jstat -gcmetacapacity <pid>
// Metaspace growing without bound after redeploys = ClassLoader leak
```

Production diagnostic:
```bash
# Count ClassLoader instances (should be stable, not growing)
jcmd <pid> VM.classloaders
# Or via jmap:
jmap -clstats <pid> | sort -k3 -rn | head -20
# Repeated hot redeploys without GC of old loaders -> Metaspace OOM
```

96.answer:
Escape analysis is a JIT compiler optimization that determines whether an object's lifetime is confined to a specific method or thread. If the JVM can prove that an object does not "escape" beyond the method that created it, it can apply powerful optimizations that eliminate heap allocation entirely.

What does "escape" mean?
```
Object ESCAPES if:
  - returned from the method
  - assigned to a static field
  - assigned to a field of another object that escapes
  - passed to a method that might store it elsewhere
  - accessed by another thread

Object does NOT escape if:
  - used only within the creating method
  - passed only to methods that are inlined (escape analysis is flow-sensitive)
```

The three key optimizations escape analysis enables:

1. Stack Allocation — object lives on the stack, not heap:
```java
// Source:
public double distanceTo(double x1, double y1, double x2, double y2) {
    Point p = new Point(x2 - x1, y2 - y1); // p never escapes!
    return Math.sqrt(p.x * p.x + p.y * p.y);
}

// After escape analysis + stack allocation:
// Point object allocated on thread stack (or in CPU registers)
// Zero heap pressure, no GC involvement, automatic cleanup on method return
// 5-10x faster than heap allocation for tight loops
```

2. Scalar Replacement — object fields become local variables (no object at all):
```java
// Source:
point p = new Point(x, y); // p doesn't escape
double dist = Math.sqrt(p.x * p.x + p.y * p.y);

// After scalar replacement (JIT internally transforms to):
double p_x = x;
double p_y = y;
double dist = Math.sqrt(p_x * p_x + p_y * p_y);
// The Point object ceases to exist entirely — fields become local vars
// These can then live in CPU registers — fastest possible access
```

3. Lock Elimination — synchronized blocks on local objects removed:
```java
// Source:
public String buildMessage(String name) {
    StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer(); // StringBuffer is synchronized
    sb.append("Hello, ").append(name).append("!");
    return sb.toString();
    // sb never escapes (returned string is a new object, not sb itself)
}

// After lock elimination:
// ALL synchronized blocks inside StringBuffer methods are eliminated
// Equivalent to using StringBuilder with zero synchronization cost
// This is why StringBuffer in local scope is as fast as StringBuilder
```

Demonstrating the effect with a benchmark:
```java
// With escape analysis (default): point objects stack-allocated
public static void benchmarkWithEA() {
    double total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < 10_000_000; i++) {
        Point p = new Point(i, i + 1); // allocated on stack
        total += p.x + p.y;
    }
    // Result: ~5ms, ZERO GC pressure, zero heap allocations
}

// Without escape analysis: -XX:-DoEscapeAnalysis
public static void benchmarkNoEA() {
    double total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < 10_000_000; i++) {
        Point p = new Point(i, i + 1); // allocated on heap!
        total += p.x + p.y;
    }
    // Result: ~50ms, 10M objects on heap, triggers GC
}
// Speedup: 10x
```

How to verify escape analysis is working:
```bash
# Enable escape analysis (default in -server mode)
-XX:+DoEscapeAnalysis

# Print escape analysis decisions
-XX:+UnlockDiagnosticVMOptions -XX:+PrintEscapeAnalysis

# Print which allocations were eliminated
-XX:+PrintEliminateAllocations

# Measure allocation rate with async-profiler
# java -agentpath:asyncProfiler.so=start,event=alloc,file=alloc.html -jar app.jar
# If escape analysis works: the Point class should not appear in allocation profile
```

When escape analysis does NOT work (object must escape):
```java
// ESCAPES: returned from method
public Point createPoint(int x, int y) {
    return new Point(x, y); // escapes -> heap allocated
}

// ESCAPES: stored in field
class Cache {
    private Point lastPoint;
    public void store(Point p) { this.lastPoint = p; } // p escapes
}

// ESCAPES: lambda captures it (may escape to thread pool)
Point p = new Point(x, y);
executor.submit(() -> process(p)); // p referenced by lambda -> escapes

// ESCAPES: too large for JIT to analyze (deeply nested methods not inlined)
// If the method calling new Point() is not inlined into the analysis scope,
// JIT conservatively assumes escape
```

Relationship to method inlining:
Escape analysis and inlining are deeply intertwined. If `getPoint()` is inlined into the calling method, the JIT can see that the returned Point doesn't actually escape the caller's scope and apply optimizations. Without inlining, the JIT cannot see across method boundaries and must assume escape.

This is why -XX:MaxInlineSize affects not just call overhead but also allocation behavior.

Production benefit areas:
- DTO construction in request/response processing pipelines
- Coordinate / vector math in game engines or spatial queries
- StringBuilder / StringBuffer usage in local methods
- Iterator objects in enhanced for loops (often stack-allocated)
- Optional<T>, Pair<A,B>, and similar wrapper types used locally
- Stream pipeline intermediate objects
